<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Admirers remembered <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> upon his death as the heart and soul of American pop music, and said his songs such as `` White Christmas,'' `` Blue Skies,'' and `` God Bless America'' will never die. The Russian cantor's son who wrote nearly 1,000 songs died Friday night in his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> townhouse at age 101. Much of his music was written for stage and movie musicals, but dozens of his songs have been performed over and over from <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> cabarets to country-western bars. Among his songs are `` Alexander's Ragtime Band,'' `` Always,'' `` <PERSON> Mandy </PERSON>,'' `` Anything You Can Do I Can Do Better,'' `` There's No Business Like Show Business,'' `` Cheek to Cheek,'' `` I've Got My Love to Keep Me Warm,'' `` Heat Wave'' and `` A Pretty Girl is Like a Melody.'' `` It's become part of our language, part of our heartbeat, part of our soul,'' said composer-conductor <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Composers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Authors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION>, which <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> helped found. `` Your songs will be with us always,'' the organization said in a full-page advertisement in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> today. `` Very few people have come to touch and move the soul of a nation,'' said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who joined a crowd of thousands in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> singing `` God <LOCATION> Bless </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' in honor of the songwriter Saturday. `` Mr. <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> ranks among such people, a composer, a legendar